Dot Product

- shows up in movement and lighting

takes 2 vectors, produces a scalar
  - also called scalar product, scalar projection

similarity of 2 vectors
  - how closely they align in direction

how to compute:
  dot(a, b) = value
  dot(a, b) = a.x * b.x + a.y * b.y

a = (1, 2), b = (1, 3)
  dot(a, b) = 1 * 1 + 2 * 3 = 7

also can be magnitude (length) of a * magnitude of b * cos(angle between a and b)
  related to the cosine of the angle between the 2 vectors, scaled by the magnitude of both

orthogonality is vectors that are perpendicular, 
  dot product is 0 and the vectors have no components in the same direction

vectors should be normalized to get dot product, direction vectors are generally normalized

for dot product 1 is same direction, -1 is opposite direction, and 0 is perpendicular

could be used to see if player is within enemy field of view 
  if enemy fov is 60deg, it's 30 on each side. so do cos(angle between where they're looking and player position), 
  if it's between 1 and cos(30) then the enemy can see the player

generally used to 
  relate the angle between 2 vectors and 
  project 1 vector onto another


